created_at refers to when the data appeared in the database, and end_date refers to the date the deal is made.

How many deals are done each year?

For the sold data, there are NAs in end_date, and some have dates way into the future. The leased data looks more normal. We should restrict the data range so that everything happens before 2020 (as it should!)

The first data dates back to 1986, but the company Property.ca Realty Inc was founded in 2008. Therefore, either these data are problematic, or they are from some other data sources. Moreover, the year 2019 and 2020 have much more data than the other years. Since our primary focus is the effects of seasonality and the effects of COVID-19, we select the data from year 2019 and 2020 only. The amount of data left is:

Times series: # of units sold or leased

Time series: price (bulk)

Since now we’re working with price data, we need to see if there’s any NA’s in both of the prices column:

We observe that, for most years, the percentage of data with missing prices (in either column) is small, and for each year after 2010 we have less than 1% of missing prices. Most notably, since 2014, the percentage of data with missing prices never exceeded 0.15%.
Normally, with missing data we may wish to analyze them and see if we can identify any pattern that is inconsistent with normal data. However, with this little missing data, it is unlikely that they would have a noticeable impact on our analysis, even if they do follow a different pattern. Therefore I simply remove the missing data.

Moreover, we observe that, in the data, there are a number of rows (about 300) where the asking price and the closed price differ by a huge amount. Some of these are incidents where the sale price is listed, but the closed_price is a rent price (or vice versa), and some others are data errors. For example, these are the cases where asked_price is more than double the closed_price (or the other way around):

These are mostly outliers and are therefore ignored in our analysis.

What are the distribution of property types for sold data and leased data?

Sold properties are 50% condos, while leased properties are 75% condos. In our price analysis, we want to look at a particular type of property, to filter out the potential confounding effects from property types.

Sale price of properties have increased by 120% from 2010 to 2020.
Rent prices, on the other hand, have grown by roughly 50% (before pandemic) over the same 10 years.
While it’s understandable that sale price and rent price do not grow together (and the types of properties being sold v.s. being leased are different), we can conduct an additional analysis to see the price per sqft, instead of the bulk price.

Time series: price (per sqft)

To calculate price per sqft, we need to first find the sqft data. There are two related variables, sqft_min and sqft_max. Since we’re only analyzing data from 2010-2020, we exclude data from other times.
How many NA’s do we have in both columns?

## # A tibble: 8 x 6
## # Groups:   type, sqft_min_na [4]
##   type   sqft_min_na sqft_max_na  count avg_asking_price avg_closed_price

## 2 leased FALSE       TRUE             2            8475             7475

We have about 20.5% of the data with at least 1 NA between sqft_min and sqft_max. In addition, we observe that

  • The most common kind of NA is NAs in both sqft_min and sqft_max. For leased properties, the average price for this category of data is similar to the average price of data with no missing sqft. For sold properties, however, the average price are much higher for listings with missing data in both sqft_min and sqft_max. Unfortunately, there is little we can do in this case, other than simply removing these rows.
  • For data with missing sqft_max but the sqft_min is not missing, the average price is very high
  • For data with missing sqft_min but the sqft_max is not missing, the average price is very low

Leased or sold data do not come with a separate sqft variable like active data, so we need to interpolate.
For cases where both sqft_min and sqft_max is available, we simply take the average.
To help us make interpolation decisions for data with missing values, let’s inspect the cases where at least one of the sqft columns is missing:

##     type sqft_min sqft_max     n
## 1 leased     5000       NA     2
## 2 leased       NA      499 18530
## 3 leased       NA      700     3
## 4 leased       NA       NA  9999
## 5   sold     5000       NA     1
## 6   sold       NA      499  7298
## 7   sold       NA      700     2
## 8   sold       NA       NA 14585

The only case for when sqft_max is missing but sqft_min is not is when the sqft exceeds 5000. In such cases we simply set the sqft to 5000.
There are two cases when sqft_min is missing but sqft_max is not. In these two cases, sqft_max is either 499 or 700.
For the case where sqft_max = 700, there are very few rows of data, so let’s remove them.
For the case where sqft_min = 499, this is actually the lowest possible value for sqft_max. We can simply assign sqft = 250 because, \(P(sqft|sqft<500)\) is not expected to follow a uniform distribution. What we can do is compare this case with the next smallest sqft_max:

## # A tibble: 4 x 6
## # Groups:   type, sqft_min [4]
##   type   sqft_min sqft_max count mean_ask_price mean_closed_price
##   <chr>     <int>    <int> <int>          <dbl>             <dbl>
## 1 leased      500      599 48314          1784.             1778.
## 2 leased       NA      499 18530          1658.             1653.
## 3 sold        500      599 21756        388287.           389143.
## 4 sold         NA      499  7298        341880.           341450.

As one can see, those with sqft_min = NA and sqft_max = 499 actually have similar average price as properties with sqft between 500 and 599 (the ratio is about 90%).
If we assume that \(P(sqft|sqft \in [500,599]) \sim Uniform(500,599)\), then we can observe that 90% of \(550 sqft\) is 495, a number very close to 499. Therefore, in this case, we simply set sqft to 499.
This actually justifies our decisions for sqft interpolation in the regression analysis.

In summary, our interpolation of sqft involves: * Taking the mean between sqft_min and sqft_max when both are non-NA * Setting sqft = 5000 when sqft_max is missing but sqft_min is not * Setting sqft = 499 when sqft_max = 499 and sqft_min is missing * Ignoring entries where sqft_max = 700 and sqft_min is missing * Ignoring entries where sqft_min and sqft_max are both NA

After interpolating sqft, we can proceed to calculate price/sqft:

The resulting graphs we got look somehow similar to the ones we got for bulk price.
The 2020:2010 ratio for sold units is roughly 2.2. This is almost identical to the bulk price case.
The ratio for leased units (2010 : 2020 before pandemic) is roughly 1.7. This is larger than the 1.5 ratio we observed in the bulk price case.
If we assume that the spatial distribution of condos for rent and for sale has not changed over the past 10 years, then this suggest that the average sqft for condos for sale has not changed, but the average sqft for condos for rent has decreased over the years.

The average sqft of condos for sale has decreased by 10% over the last 10 years, but the average sqft of condos for rent has decreased by 20% over the past 10 years.
